<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Lansdale, PA: 6 Jan 02<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.86)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=498'>Doug "Phrim" Faust</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=498&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 11, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Tournament Report - Sun 6 Jan 02<br>
NeoQuest Games in Lansdale, PA<br>
<br>
Well, this is the first tournament report I&#39;ve written for LOTRtcg.  I&#39;ve been to a few tournaments before this one, and I guess I could&#39;ve written some for those, but for some reason I can&#39;t remember LOTR games as well as I could SW games.  But I&#39;ve got to start somewhere I guess...<br>
<br>
So anyway, I&#39;ve never been to the store before, so I ask Kim, the TD, for directions.  She sends me on some roundabout route, so I use Expedia Maps (which is better than Mapquest) to get myself a better route, albeit all back roads.  So anyway, I get to the place at 12pm, and there&#39;s no one there.  So I talk to the store owner a bit, and it turns out the tournament doesn&#39;t start until 2pm.  Doh.  Could&#39;ve sworn it said 12, but whatever.  So I decide to go get some lunch, but then I see Kim and George Gundry drive up.  So I talk to them for a bit and then head over to subway to get some lunch.<br>
<br>
So I eat lunch, trade a bit, and then I play Bob Caton in a fun game: my Gandalf/Moria weapon deck against his Dwarves.  My deck works pretty well, and his minions can&#39;t really do much to my companions, and I only manage to kill a few Dwarf Guards.  But I went first, so I win at site 9.  In the meantime, a bunch more people show up, and we end up with 11 people.  Here&#39;s the lineup: myself (1586, #4 in NY), John Lolli (1581, #1 in NJ), Mike Dalton (1575, #2 in NJ), Kim Caton (1565, #2 in PA), Bob Caton (1554, #4 in PA), Greg Shaw (1516), and 5 people who haven&#39;t played in LOTR tournaments yet: Scott Landis, George Gundry, Bill Kafer, Ted Panczyszyn (see, I can spell it!), and one guy who I didn&#39;t know.  So all in all, it was pretty good competition.<br>
<br>
My deck is the same one I&#39;ve been using at tournaments for a long time now, the fellowship side uses the fairly standard &quot;big beefy companion&quot; strategy, abusing the Legolas/Aragorn&#39;s Bow angle, but not using other archery for fear of Relentless Charge and the such.  Shadow is a straight Sauron deck, that uses 4x UTWE, 4x Orc Bowmen, and 4x Hate to do lots and lots of direct damage.  The original version of the deck is posted on my member page.<br>
<br>
Game 1: Mike Dalton&#39;s (1575) Pool Denial/Moria Swarm<br>
<br>
This is an interesting first round matchup, seeing as we talk a lot online, and at the last tournament I went to, we faced off in the final game to determine 1st place (and I won).  Anyway, apparently Mike got tired of the Nazgul deck he was using in tournaments before today, and was playing his version of Alex Tennet&#39;s pool denial deck that I&#39;ve been having trouble beating in playtesting.  The deck starts only the rare Aragorn, its only companion, and revolves around giving the opponent as little pool as possible, while moving slowly and relying on its Moria half to overwhelm.  I bid 2 and go first, but my opening hand is 7 Shadow cards and 1 Fellowship card (Aragorn&#39;s Bow).  This is a horrible start against his deck, because getting Shadow cards out of your hand is incredibly hard.  So I play Aragorn from my deck and give him his Bow, and breeze through the first two sites regardless.  On his turn, he plays Sting and something else, but then removes the pool with Sting.  Fortunately for me, he didn&#39;t get a No Stranger right away, so he gives me 3 pool.  I can do stuff with 3 pool, but I can do absolutely nothing with 2.  So I play an Ambusher and drop an UTWE, getting 2 of the Shadow cards out of my hand.  I think he stopped at site 2 or something, being somewhat insistant on moving as slow as physically possible.  So anyway, since he was significantly behind me, I started moving one site at a time as well.  I managed to get to Lorien with everyone still alive, though many of my companions were exhausted.  However, I have some Athelas and whatnot in my hand, so I move to site 7 with only one or two wounds on my entire party.  His site 7, however, was the anti-archery site.  This is bad for my deck, and he manages to add pool with Armories and get minions with stuff like They Are Coming and Host of Thousands, so he has 6 minions to my 5 companions.  Without the Archery, I have no way to get rid of the excess minions, so Frodo gets overwhelmed.  FL, Total: 1 pt<br>
<br>
Highlights: Being able to take it one site at a time because he was so far behind.<br>
Lowlights: The no-archery site lost me the game...<br>
<br>
Game 2: Bill Kafer&#39;s (unrated) Nazgul/Sauron Discard Deck<br>
<br>
Bill&#39;s deck is fairly standard on the companion side, but for his Shadows he&#39;s got a bunch of Nazgul mixed with those big beefy Sauron Orcs that make you discard, plus a bunch of stuff like Desperate Defense of the Ring and Thin and Stretched.  He&#39;s playing Nazgul, so I go first, and I don&#39;t have that much trouble getting to site 3.  Bill, apparently, got a really good companion draw, and has uber-companions that I can&#39;t touch.  So it basically turns into a race.  I manage to kill Sam with a Morgul Hunter (big accomplishment there, I know), and he plays Desperate Defense on both Aragorn and Boromir, and Thin and Stretched, and an Irresistable Shadow (if that ever happens I&#39;ll shoot myself), plus some other Nazgul thing that I can&#39;t remember (Drawn to Its Power maybe?).  I end up taking a burden that first turn Thin and Stretched comes down because I definitely don&#39;t want to fight with Frodo, but the turn after that I play Versatility so there&#39;s no fight to begin with.  I end up skipping the second sanctuary because I&#39;m racing.  So here I am, at site 7, with 5 companions (Frodo, Arwen, Legolas, Aragorn, Boromir), a whole cartload of Shadow conditions everywhere, and Gandalf and a Sleep in my hand.  I decide risking Enquea is worth me getting rid of all those conditions, because heck, he&#39;s only playing half Nazgul, what&#39;re the chances he&#39;s got Enquea waiting for me.  So I play Gandalf and Sleep away everything, move, and of course he drops Enquea with 3 other big beefy guys.  So Enquea exerts 3 times to kill of Aragorn, Legolas exerts to kill Enquea, Arwen takes the Nazgul, and Boromir and Gandalf take the 2 big Orcs.  Arwen wins her fight because she has Gwemegil, but Boromir gets overwhelmed because of Enduring Evil (doh), and then Gandalf gets overwhelmed because of another Enduring Evil (double doh).  So he kills off my three biggest companions in one turn, lovely.  I do stop because he can&#39;t win next turn, so he does his thing and then my turn comes around again.  So I move, but he&#39;s only got one minion for me, so I win.  FW, Total: 4 pts<br>
<br>
Highlights: Blowing up all the conditions with Sleep<br>
Lowlights: Getting 3 big guys killed in one turn<br>
<br>
Game 3: Kim Caton&#39;s (1565) Archery/Nazgul<br>
<br>
I wasn&#39;t too surprised about the contents of Kim&#39;s deck, it was a pretty typical companion archers minion nazgul deck.  You know, the good ol&#39; put bows on lots of elves, and play a variety of nazgul with the whole Black Breath/Blade Tip thing going on.  So anyway, I go first by bidding 2, and get Aragorn in my opening hand.  This turns out to be huge, as she&#39;s playing lots of Nazgul Swords, and I don&#39;t have to add the 3rd burden to fetch Aragorn and make all the swords nasty.  So I go as fast as I can, but I get loaded up with conditions and stuff.  I combat that the best I can with Athelas and Sleep, and keep moving.  Kim&#39;s archery pretty much prevents me from ever actually skirmishing with her, but I do manage to kill Legolas with a Hate.  In the end, this game also turns into a race, so I skip the second sanctuary again, and despite all the her nazgul and condition goodies, she can&#39;t stop me or make up for going second.  So she ends up at site 8, and I get to site 9 and win.  FW, Total: 7 pts<br>
<br>
Highlights: Well killing Legolas is always fun...<br>
Lowlights: I hate Black Breath<br>
<br>
Game 4: John Lolli&#39;s (1581) Gandalf/Nazgul<br>
<br>
John combined a typical Nazgul deck with a deck starting Gandalf and using all his spells.  I know this deck could be a problem for me, because Sleep counters all my conditions, and Intimidate counters my Hates.  So I bid 2 and go first again, and again I manage to stay in the lead the entire game.  Meanwhile, I get a pretty good Shadow draw, so I drop 2 Bowmen and 2 UTWE on him as he gets to Rivendell.  So he&#39;s starting to get hurt by all my conditions and stuff, and I manage to kill Boromir.  In the meantime, he keeps talking about needing to draw a Sleep to make all my conditions go away.  He moves and puts one of the exerts from UTWE on Gandalf.  I have 3 Hates in my hand, so I could theoretically kill Gandalf with them, or if he has an Intimidate, at least exhaust him so he can&#39;t play Sleep.  So I play a Morgul Hunter and give it a go, and I do kill Gandalf.  And it was right at the right time apparently, as he had a Sleep and 3 other Gandalf spells in his hand that he couldn&#39;t play.  A couple turns later, I draw my last Hate and kill the exhausted Legolas.  So he&#39;s hurting pretty bad.  On the other hand, I&#39;m not having too much problems.  He expects me to stay at site 6, but I skip it because I can.  In the end I make it to site 9, and he&#39;s pretty beat up.  FW, Total: 10 pts.<br>
<br>
Highlights: Killing Gandalf right before he Slept!<br>
Lowlights: None, really, both sides of the deck worked perfectly.<br>
<br>
So anyway, there was some talk of doing a final confrontation, or even playing another round, but Mike Dalton was the only undefeated and wanted neither to jeopardize this status.  A final confrontation would have been difficult anyway, because as it turns out, myself and Scott Landis were tied for second place--on opposition total and everything.  Both of us were 3-1 with our only losses to Mike.  So what we really needed to do was to determine who would get 2nd, not 1st. :-)  So myself and Scott decide to play a &quot;final confrontation&quot; to decide who gets second...<br>
<br>
Playoffs: Scott Landis&#39;s (unrated) Nazgul with Tricks<br>
<br>
Don&#39;t really remember too much of what Scott was playing for the Fellowship side, as it seemed like he got a lot of it out in the few couple turns, but his Shadow side was a fairly unconventional Nazgul, he didn&#39;t go all out on the Blade Tip/Black Breath angle, but used a lot of other stuff that helped him out at times.  So anyway, I get a really good opening hand, with Gandalf, Glamdring, and Gwemegil.  So he has a tough time stopping me, though he does keep doing annoying stuff like playing that card to heal a Nazgul when he&#39;s about to die, and one of the cards to add power to a Nazgul when I thought I would win.  Regardless, I&#39;m able to stay ahead for most of the game.  He&#39;s got a pretty decent fellowship as well, so I&#39;m hard pressed to do anything to him.  I have 2 Hates in my hand, and I could kill people with it, but he uses A Ranger&#39;s Versatility two turns in a row to prevent me from using them at all.  In the end, he&#39;s at site 8, but I get to site 9 first and win.<br>
<br>
So I win that game and take 2nd and the nifty little certificate thing.  Now if I can only get a &quot;participant award&quot; I&#39;ll have a complete set, though that one might be harder since I won&#39;t get it if I place first or second. :-)  So I think about sticking around for a little longer, but the weather was starting to get ugly with sleet and stuff, so I take off.<br>
<br>
Props:<br>
<br>
- Kim Caton for running a great tournament<br>
- NeoQuest Games for the nice tables and chairs :-)<br>
- Mike Dalton for winning<br>
- Scott Landis for doing well despite it being his first LOTR tournament<br>
- Bill Kafer for not beating me with my own cards :-)<br>
- Ted Panczyszyn for being himself<br>
<br>
Slops:<br>
<br>
- Ugly weather<br>
<br>
Until next time...<br>
<br>
